《學而》
1 子曰：「學而時習之，不亦說乎？有朋自遠方來，不亦樂乎？人不知而不慍，不亦君子乎？」
2 有子曰：「其為人也孝弟，而好犯上者，鮮矣；不好犯上，而好作亂者，未之有也。君子務本，本立而道生。孝弟也者，其為仁之本與！」 Xue Er: The philosopher You said, &ldquo;They are few who, being filial and fraternal, are fond of offending against their superiors. There have been none, who, not liking to offend against their superiors, have been fond of stirring up confusion. The superior man bends his attention to what is radical. That being established, all practical courses naturally grow up. Filial piety and fraternal submission! - are they not the root of all benevolent actions?&rdquo;
3 Jump to dictionaryShow parallel passagesShow commentaryRelated discussionShow additional information	學而: 子曰：「巧言令色，鮮矣仁！」 Xue Er: The Master said, &ldquo;Fine words and an insinuating appearance are seldom associated with true virtue.&rdquo; 4 Jump to dictionaryShow parallel passagesShow commentaryRelated discussionShow additional information	學而: 曾子曰：「吾日三省吾身：為人謀而不忠乎？與朋友交而不信乎？傳不習乎？」 Xue Er: The philosopher Zeng said, &ldquo;I daily examine myself on three points: whether, in transacting business for others, I may have been not faithful; whether, in intercourse with friends, I may have been not sincere; whether I may have not mastered and practiced the instructions of my teacher.&rdquo; 5 Jump to dictionaryShow parallel passagesShow commentaryShow additional information	學而: 子曰：「道千乘之國：敬事而信，節用而愛人，使民以時。」 Xue Er: The Master said, &ldquo;To rule a country of a thousand chariots, there must be reverent attention to business, and sincerity; economy in expenditure, and love for men; and the employment of the people at the proper seasons.&rdquo; 6 Jump to dictionaryShow parallel passagesShow commentaryShow additional information	學而: 子曰：「弟子入則孝，出則弟，謹而信，汎愛眾，而親仁。行有餘力，則以學文。」 Xue Er: The Master said, &ldquo;A youth, when at home, should be filial, and, abroad, respectful to his elders. He should be earnest and truthful. He should overflow in love to all, and cultivate the friendship of the good. When he has time and opportunity, after the performance of these things, he should employ them in polite studies.&rdquo; 7 Jump to dictionaryShow parallel passagesShow commentaryShow additional information	學而: 子夏曰：「賢賢易色，事父母能竭其力，事君能致其身，與朋友交言而有信。雖曰未學，吾必謂之學矣。」 Xue Er: Zi Xia said, &ldquo;If a man withdraws his mind from the love of beauty, and applies it as sincerely to the love of the virtuous; if, in serving his parents, he can exert his utmost strength; if, in serving his prince, he can devote his life; if, in his intercourse with his friends, his words are sincere - although men say that he has not learned, I will certainly say that he has.&rdquo; 8 Jump to dictionaryShow parallel passagesShow commentaryRelated discussionShow additional information	學而: 子曰：「君子不重則不威，學則不固。主忠信，無友不如己者，過則勿憚改。」 Xue Er: The Master said, &ldquo;If the scholar be not grave, he will not call forth any veneration, and his learning will not be solid. Hold faithfulness and sincerity as first principles. Have no friends not equal to yourself. When you have faults, do not fear to abandon them.&rdquo; 9 Jump to dictionaryShow parallel passagesShow commentaryShow additional information	學而: 曾子曰：「慎終追遠，民德歸厚矣。」 Xue Er: The philosopher Zeng said, &ldquo;Let there be a careful attention to perform the funeral rites to parents, and let them be followed when long gone with the ceremonies of sacrifice - then the virtue of the people will resume its proper excellence.&rdquo; 10 Jump to dictionaryShow parallel passagesShow commentaryShow additional information	學而: 子禽問於子貢曰：「夫子至於是邦也，必聞其政，求之與？抑與之與？」子貢曰：「夫子溫、良、恭、儉、讓以得之。夫子之求之也，其諸異乎人之求之與？」 Xue Er: Zi Qin asked Zi Gong, saying, &ldquo;When our master comes to any country, he does not fail to learn all about its government. Does he ask his information? or is it given to him?&rdquo; Zi Gong said, &ldquo;Our master is benign, upright, courteous, temperate, and complaisant and thus he gets his information. The master&rsquo;s mode of asking information! - is it not different from that of other men?&rdquo; 11 Jump to dictionaryShow parallel passagesShow commentaryShow additional information	學而: 子曰：「父在，觀其志；父沒，觀其行；三年無改於父之道，可謂孝矣。」 Xue Er: The Master said, &ldquo;While a man&rsquo;s father is alive, look at the bent of his will; when his father is dead, look at his conduct. If for three years he does not alter from the way of his father, he may be called filial.&rdquo; 12 Jump to dictionaryShow parallel passagesShow commentaryRelated discussionShow additional information	學而: 有子曰：「禮之用，和為貴。先王之道斯為美，小大由之。有所不行，知和而和，不以禮節之，亦不可行也。」 Xue Er: The philosopher You said, &ldquo;In practicing the rules of propriety, a natural ease is to be prized. In the ways prescribed by the ancient kings, this is the excellent quality, and in things small and great we follow them. Yet it is not to be observed in all cases. If one, knowing how such ease should be prized, manifests it, without regulating it by the rules of propriety, this likewise is not to be done.&rdquo; 13 Jump to dictionaryShow parallel passagesShow commentaryRelated discussionShow additional information	學而: 有子曰：「信近於義，言可復也；恭近於禮，遠恥辱也；因不失其親，亦可宗也。」 Xue Er: The philosopher You said, &ldquo;When agreements are made according to what is right, what is spoken can be made good. When respect is shown according to what is proper, one keeps far from shame and disgrace. When the parties upon whom a man leans are proper persons to be intimate with, he can make them his guides and masters.&rdquo; 14 Jump to dictionaryShow parallel passagesShow commentaryRelated discussionShow additional information	學而: 子曰：「君子食無求飽，居無求安，敏於事而慎於言，就有道而正焉，可謂好學也已。」 Xue Er: The Master said, &ldquo;He who aims to be a man of complete virtue in his food does not seek to gratify his appetite, nor in his dwelling place does he seek the appliances of ease; he is earnest in what he is doing, and careful in his speech; he frequents the company of men of principle that he may be rectified - such a person may be said indeed to love to learn.&rdquo; 15 Jump to dictionaryShow parallel passagesShow commentaryShow additional information	學而: 子貢曰：「貧而無諂，富而無驕，何如？」子曰：「可也。未若貧而樂1，富而好禮者也。」子貢曰：「《詩》云：『如切如磋，如琢如磨。』其斯之謂與？」子曰：「賜也，始可與言詩已矣！告諸往而知來者。」 Xue Er: Zi Gong said, &ldquo;What do you pronounce concerning the poor man who yet does not flatter, and the rich man who is not proud?&rdquo; The Master replied, &ldquo;They will do; but they are not equal to him, who, though poor, is yet cheerful, and to him, who, though rich, loves the rules of propriety.&rdquo; Zi Gong replied, &ldquo;It is said in the Book of Poetry, &lsquo;As you cut and then file, as you carve and then polish.&rsquo; - The meaning is the same, I apprehend, as that which you have just expressed.&rdquo; The Master said, &ldquo;With one like Ci, I can begin to talk about the odes. I told him one point, and he knew its proper sequence.&rdquo;
 樂 : Another version reads: &ldquo;樂道&rdquo;. 《知不足齋叢書》本、《古逸叢書》本《論語集解》作「樂道」。  16 Jump to dictionaryShow parallel passagesShow commentaryRelated discussionShow additional information	學而: 子曰：「不患人之不己知，患不知人也。」 Xue Er: The Master said, &ldquo;I will not be afflicted at men&rsquo;s not knowing me; I will be afflicted that I do not know men.&rdquo;

《為政》
1子曰：「為政以德，譬如北辰，居其所而眾星共之。」
2子曰：「詩三百，一言以蔽之，曰『思無邪』。」 Wei Zheng: The Master said, &ldquo;In the Book of Poetry are three hundred pieces, but the design of them all may be embraced in one sentence - &lsquo;Having no depraved thoughts.'&rdquo; 3 Jump to dictionaryShow parallel passagesShow commentaryRelated discussionShow additional information	為政: 子曰：「道之以政，齊之以刑，民免而無恥；道之以德，齊之以禮，有恥且格。」 Wei Zheng: The Master said, &ldquo;If the people be led by laws, and uniformity sought to be given them by punishments, they will try to avoid the punishment, but have no sense of shame. If they be led by virtue, and uniformity sought to be given them by the rules of propriety, they will have the sense of shame, and moreover will become good.&rdquo; 4 Jump to dictionaryShow parallel passagesShow commentaryShow additional information	為政: 子曰：「吾十有五而志于學，三十而立，四十而不惑，五十而知天命，六十而耳順，七十而從心所欲，不踰矩。」 Wei Zheng: The Master said, &ldquo;At fifteen, I had my mind bent on learning. At thirty, I stood firm. At forty, I had no doubts. At fifty, I knew the decrees of Heaven. At sixty, my ear was an obedient organ for the reception of truth. At seventy, I could follow what my heart desired, without transgressing what was right.&rdquo; 5 Jump to dictionaryShow parallel passagesShow commentaryShow additional information	為政: 孟懿子問孝。子曰：「無違。」樊遲御，子告之曰：「孟孫問孝於我，我對曰『無違』。」樊遲曰：「何謂也？」子曰：「生事之以禮；死葬之以禮，祭之以禮。」 Wei Zheng: Meng Yi asked what filial piety was. The Master said, &ldquo;It is not being disobedient.&rdquo; Soon after, as Fan Chi was driving him, the Master told him, saying, &ldquo;Meng-sun asked me what filial piety was, and I answered him, - &lsquo;not being disobedient.'&rdquo; Fan Chi said, &ldquo;What did you mean?&rdquo; The Master replied, &ldquo;That parents, when alive, be served according to propriety; that, when dead, they should be buried according to propriety; and that they should be sacrificed to according to propriety.&rdquo; 6 Jump to dictionaryShow parallel passagesShow commentaryRelated discussionShow additional information	為政: 孟武伯問孝。子曰：「父母唯其疾之憂。」 Wei Zheng: Meng Wu asked what filial piety was. The Master said, &ldquo;Parents are anxious lest their children should be sick.&rdquo; 7 Jump to dictionaryShow parallel passagesShow commentaryShow additional information	為政: 子游問孝。子曰：「今之孝者，是謂能養。至於犬馬，皆能有養；不敬，何以別乎？」 Wei Zheng: Zi You asked what filial piety was. The Master said, &ldquo;The filial piety nowadays means the support of one&rsquo;s parents. But dogs and horses likewise are able to do something in the way of support; - without reverence, what is there to distinguish the one support given from the other?&rdquo; 8 Jump to dictionaryShow commentaryRelated discussionShow additional information	為政: 子夏問孝。子曰：「色難。有事弟子服其勞，有酒食先生饌，曾是以為孝乎？」 Wei Zheng: Zi Xia asked what filial piety was. The Master said, &ldquo;The difficulty is with the countenance. If, when their elders have any troublesome affairs, the young take the toil of them, and if, when the young have wine and food, they set them before their elders, is THIS to be considered filial piety?&rdquo; 9 Jump to dictionaryShow parallel passagesShow commentaryRelated discussionShow additional information	為政: 子曰：「吾與回言終日，不違如愚。退而省其私，亦足以發。回也，不愚。」 Wei Zheng: The Master said, &ldquo;I have talked with Hui for a whole day, and he has not made any objection to anything I said - as if he were stupid. He has retired, and I have examined his conduct when away from me, and found him able to illustrate my teachings. Hui! - He is not stupid.&rdquo; 10 Jump to dictionaryShow parallel passagesShow commentaryShow additional information	為政: 子曰：「視其所以，觀其所由，察其所安。人焉廋哉？人焉廋哉？」 Wei Zheng: The Master said, &ldquo;See what a man does. Mark his motives. Examine in what things he rests. How can a man conceal his character? How can a man conceal his character?&rdquo; 11 Jump to dictionaryShow parallel passagesShow commentaryShow additional information	為政: 子曰：「溫故而知新，可以為師矣。」 Wei Zheng: The Master said, &ldquo;If a man keeps cherishing his old knowledge, so as continually to be acquiring new, he may be a teacher of others.&rdquo; 12 Jump to dictionaryShow commentaryRelated discussionShow additional information	為政: 子曰：「君子不器。」 Wei Zheng: The Master said, &ldquo;The accomplished scholar is not a utensil.&rdquo; 13 Jump to dictionaryShow commentaryRelated discussionShow additional information	為政: 子貢問君子。子曰：「先行其言，而後從之。」 Wei Zheng: Zi Gong asked what constituted the superior man. The Master said, &ldquo;He acts before he speaks, and afterwards speaks according to his actions.&rdquo; 14 Jump to dictionaryShow parallel passagesShow commentaryShow additional information	為政: 子曰：「君子周而不比，小人比而不周。」 Wei Zheng: The Master said, &ldquo;The superior man is catholic and not partisan. The mean man is partisan and not catholic.&rdquo; 15 Jump to dictionaryShow parallel passagesShow commentaryShow additional information	為政: 子曰：「學而不思則罔，思而不學則殆。」 Wei Zheng: The Master said, &ldquo;Learning without thought is labor lost; thought without learning is perilous.&rdquo; 16 Jump to dictionaryShow parallel passagesShow commentaryRelated discussionShow additional information	為政: 子曰：「攻乎異端，斯害也已！」 Wei Zheng: The Master said, &ldquo;The study of strange doctrines is injurious indeed!&rdquo; 17 Jump to dictionaryShow parallel passagesShow commentaryShow additional information	為政: 子曰：「由！誨女知之乎？知之為知之，不知為不知，是知也。」 Wei Zheng: The Master said, &ldquo;You, shall I teach you what knowledge is? When you know a thing, to hold that you know it; and when you do not know a thing, to allow that you do not know it - this is knowledge.&rdquo; 18 Jump to dictionaryShow parallel passagesShow commentaryShow additional information	為政: 子張學干祿。子曰：「多聞闕疑，慎言其餘，則寡尤；多見闕殆，慎行其餘，則寡悔。言寡尤，行寡悔，祿在其中矣。」 Wei Zheng: Zi Zhang was learning with a view to official emolument. The Master said, &ldquo;Hear much and put aside the points of which you stand in doubt, while you speak cautiously at the same time of the others - then you will afford few occasions for blame. See much and put aside the things which seem perilous, while you are cautious at the same time in carrying the others into practice - then you will have few occasions for repentance. When one gives few occasions for blame in his words, and few occasions for repentance in his conduct, he is in the way to get emolument.&rdquo; 19 Jump to dictionaryShow parallel passagesShow commentaryShow additional information	為政: 哀公問曰：「何為則民服？」孔子對曰：「舉直錯諸枉，則民服；舉枉錯諸直，則民不服。」 Wei Zheng: The Duke Ai asked, saying, &ldquo;What should be done in order to secure the submission of the people?&rdquo; Confucius replied, &ldquo;Advance the upright and set aside the crooked, then the people will submit. Advance the crooked and set aside the upright, then the people will not submit.&rdquo; 20 Jump to dictionaryShow parallel passagesShow commentaryRelated discussionShow additional information	為政: 季康子問：「使民敬、忠以勸，如之何？」子曰：「臨之以莊則敬，孝慈則忠，舉善而教不能，則勸。」 Wei Zheng: Ji Kang asked how to cause the people to reverence their ruler, to be faithful to him, and to go on to nerve themselves to virtue. The Master said, &ldquo;Let him preside over them with gravity; then they will reverence him. Let him be final and kind to all; then they will be faithful to him. Let him advance the good and teach the incompetent; then they will eagerly seek to be virtuous.&rdquo; 21 Jump to dictionaryShow parallel passagesShow commentaryShow additional information	為政: 或謂孔子曰：「子奚不為政？」子曰：「《書》云：『孝乎惟孝、友于兄弟，施於有政。』是亦為政，奚其為為政？」 Wei Zheng: Some one addressed Confucius, saying, &ldquo;Sir, why are you not engaged in the government?&rdquo; The Master said, &ldquo;What does the Shu Jing say of filial piety? - &lsquo;You are filial, you discharge your brotherly duties. These qualities are displayed in government.&rsquo; This then also constitutes the exercise of government. Why must there be THAT - making one be in the government?&rdquo; 22 Jump to dictionaryShow parallel passagesShow commentaryShow additional information	為政: 子曰：「人而無信，不知其可也。大車無輗，小車無軏，其何以行之哉？」 Wei Zheng: The Master said, &ldquo;I do not know how a man without truthfulness is to get on. How can a large carriage be made to go without the crossbar for yoking the oxen to, or a small carriage without the arrangement for yoking the horses?&rdquo; 23 Jump to dictionaryShow parallel passagesShow commentaryShow additional information	為政: 子張問：「十世可知也？」子曰：「殷因於夏禮，所損益，可知也；周因於殷禮，所損益，可知也；其或繼周者，雖百世可知也。」 Wei Zheng: Zi Zhang asked whether the affairs of ten ages after could be known. Confucius said, &ldquo;The Yin dynasty followed the regulations of the Xia; wherein it took from or added to them may be known. The Zhou dynasty has followed the regulations of Yin; wherein it took from or added to them may be known. Some other may follow the Zhou, but though it should be at the distance of a hundred ages, its affairs may be known.&rdquo; 24 Jump to dictionaryShow parallel passagesShow commentaryShow additional information	為政: 子曰：「非其鬼而祭之，諂也。見義不為，無勇也。」 Wei Zheng: The Master said, &ldquo;For a man to sacrifice to a spirit which does not belong to him is flattery. To see what is right and not to do it is want of courage.&rdquo;

