 has not learned, I will certainly say that he has.&rdquo; 8 Jump to dictionaryShow parallel passagesShow commentaryRelated discussionShow additional information	學而: 子曰：「君子不重則不威，學則不固。主忠信，無友不如己者，過則勿憚改。」 Xue Er: The Master said, &ldquo;If the scholar be not grave, he will not call forth any veneration, and his learning will not be solid. Hold faithfulness and sincerity as first principles. Have no friends not equal to yourself. When you have faults, do not fear to abandon them.&rdquo; 9 Jump to dictionaryShow parallel passagesShow commentaryShow additional information	學而: 曾子曰：「慎終追遠，民德歸厚矣。」 Xue Er: The philosopher Zeng said, &ldquo;Let there be a careful attention to perform the funeral rites to parents, and let them be followed when long gone with the ceremonies of sacrifice - then the virtue of the people will resume its proper excellence.&rdquo; 10 Jump to dictionaryShow parallel passagesShow commentaryShow additional information	學而: 子禽問於子貢曰：「夫子至於是邦也，必聞其政，求之與？抑與之與？」子貢曰：「夫子溫、良、恭、儉、讓以得之。夫子之求之也，其諸異乎人之求之與？」 Xue Er: Zi Qin asked Zi Gong, saying, &ldquo;When our master comes to any country, he does not fail to learn all about its government. Does he ask his information? or is it given to him?&rdquo; Zi Gong said, &ldquo;Our master is benign, upright, courteous, temperate, and complaisant and thus he gets his information. The master&rsquo;s mode of asking information! - is it not different from that of other men?&rdquo; 11 Jump to dictionaryShow parallel passagesShow commentaryShow additional information	學而: 子曰：「父在，觀其志；父沒，觀其行；三年無改於父之道，可謂孝矣。」 Xue Er: The Master said, &ldquo;While a man&rsquo;s father is alive, look at the bent of his will; when his father is dead, look at his conduct. If for three years he does not alter from the way of his father, he may be called filial.&rdquo; 12 Jump to dictionaryShow parallel passagesShow commentaryRelated discussionShow additional information	學而: 有子曰：「禮之用，和為貴。先王之道斯為美，小大由之。有所不行，知和而和，不以禮節之，亦不可行也。」 Xue Er: The philosopher You said, &ldquo;In practicing the rules of propriety, a natural ease is to be prized. In the ways prescribed by the ancient kings, this is the excellent quality, and in things small and great we follow them. Yet it is not to be observed in all cases. If one, knowing how such ease should be prized, manifests it, without regulating it by the rules of propriety, this likewise is not to be done.&rdquo; 13 Jump to dictionaryShow parallel passagesShow commentaryRelated discussionShow additional information	學而: 有子曰：「信近於義，言可復也；恭近於禮，遠恥辱也；因不失其親，亦可宗也。」 Xue Er: The philosopher You said, &ldquo;When agreements are made according to what is right, what is spoken can be made good. When respect is shown according to what is proper, one keeps far from shame and disgrace. When the parties upon whom a man leans are proper persons to be intimate with, he can make them his guides and masters.&rdquo; 14 Jump to dictionaryShow parallel passagesShow commentaryRelated discussionShow additional information	學而: 子曰：「君子食無求飽，居無求安，敏於事而慎於言，就有道而正焉，可謂好學也已。」 Xue Er: The Master said, &ldquo;He who aims to be a man of complete virtue in his food does not seek to gratify his appetite, nor in his dwelling place does he seek the appliances of ease; he is earnest in what he is doing, and careful in his speech; he frequents the company of men of principle that he may be rectified - such a person may be said indeed to love to learn.&rdquo; 15 Jump to dictionaryShow parallel passagesShow commentaryShow additional information	學而: 子貢曰：「貧而無諂，富而無驕，何如？」子曰：「可也。未若貧而樂1，富而好禮者也。」子貢曰：「《詩》云：『如切如磋，如琢如磨。』其斯之謂與？」子曰：「賜也，始可與言詩已矣！告諸往而知來者。」 Xue Er: Zi Gong said, &ldquo;What do you pronounce concerning the poor man who yet does not flatter, and the rich man who is not proud?&rdquo; The Master replied, &ldquo;They will do; but they are not equal to him, who, though poor, is yet cheerful, and to him, who, though rich, loves the rules of propriety.&rdquo; Zi Gong replied, &ldquo;It is said in the Book of Poetry, &lsquo;As you cut and then file, 